<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-306-448  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 306 448.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  April 2 1990 v24 n14 p96(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Xerox loses the first skirmish to Apple. (Xerox Corp. law suitalleging copyright infringement by Apple Computer Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Daly, James.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Xerox Corp loses the first round of its $150 million law suitagainst Apple Computer Inc in US District Court in San Francisco,CA.andP;  The suit alleges that Apple Computer Inc infringed oncopyrights held by Xerox for graphical user interface technology(GUI) developed in Xerox's Star project during the 1970s.andO;According to Xerox, Apple used this technology in creating thewindows-and-icons design for its Lisa and Macintosh lines ofmicrocomputers.andP;  Judge Vaughn Walker dismissed five of six countsand prompted Xerox attorneys to announce that they would appealthe case.andP;  The suit sought $100 million compensation for revenuediverted to Apple and $50 million for alleged damages to Xerox'sbusiness.andP;  The suit was weakened, according to observers, by thefact that it was filed long after the 1984 introduction of theApple Macintosh microcomputer that incorporates the disputedtechnology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Xerox Corp. (cases)Apple Computer Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    XRX; AAPL.andO;Topic:     Law SuitCopyrightGraphical User InterfaceProductsCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>